04747nam a22007215i 9780231556002DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2022008900  a97802315560027 a10.7312/herr205442doi  a(DE-B1597)638382  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPS153.O43 4aPS153.O43bH47 2022 7aLIT0240502bisacsh04a700.84/60973223/eng/202206291 aHerring, Scott, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAging Moderns :bArt, Literature, and the Experiment of Later Life /cScott Herring. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIllustrations -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: Experimental Aging and American Modernism -- tChapter 1 Djuna Barnes and the Geriatric Avant- Garde -- tChapter 2 The Special Collections of Samuel Steward -- tChapter 3 Ivan Albright’s Anti- Antiaging Treatments -- tChapter 4 Tillie Olsen and the Old- Old Left -- tChapter 5 Queer Senior Living with Charles Henri Ford and Indra Bahadur Tamang -- tChapter 6 The Harlem Renaissance as Told by “Lesbian Elder” Mabel Hampton -- tCoda: After Jacob Lawrence at Iona Senior Services -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat happens when the avant-garde grows old? Examining a group of writers and artists who continued the modernist experiment into later life, Scott Herring reveals how their radical artistic principles set out a new path for creative aging.Aging Moderns provides portraits of writers and artists who sought out or employed unconventional methods and collaborations up until the early twenty-first century. Herring finds Djuna Barnes performing the principles of high modernism not only in poetry but also in pharmacy orders and grocery lists. In mystery novels featuring Gertrude Stein and Alice B. Toklas along with modernist souvenir collections, the gay writer Samuel Steward elaborated a queer theory of aging and challenged gay male ageism. The Harlem Renaissance dancer Mabel Hampton dispelled stereotypes about aging through her queer of color performances at the Lesbian Herstory Archives. Herring explores Ivan Albright’s magic realist portraits of elders, Tillie Olsen’s writings on the aging female worker, and the surrealistic works made by Charles Henri Ford and his caregiver Indra Bahadur Tamang at the Dakota apartment building in New York City.Showcasing previously unpublished experimental art and writing, this deeply interdisciplinary book unites new modernist studies, American studies, disability studies, and critical age studies. Aging Moderns rethinks assumptions about literary creativity, the depiction of old age, and the boundaries of modernism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aAging in art. 0aAging in literature. 0aAmerican literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aArt and older people. 0aArt, Americany20th centuryxHistory. 0aModernism (Art)zUnited States. 0aModernism (Literature)zUnited States. 0aOlder people's writings, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Modern / 20th Century .2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311074966340uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/herr2054440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231556002423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231556002/original  a978-3-11-074966-3  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPD